"&#xa0;\nWritten evidence from the Professional Standards Authority for Health andSocial Care (NMC 0011)&#xa0;\nTotal case meetings heldTotal NMC case meetings heldNMC Appeals201011\n7\n3\n201110\n5\n1\n201215\n8\n2\n2013 (to date)10\n4\n1\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n \n              \nCase meetings are internal panels held with our lawyer present where we decide whether or not a particular case meets the threshold for an appeal to the Courts in the public interest.\n \n              \nHealth Committee\n,\n 2013. Oral Evidence from Professional Standards Authority for Health and Social Care. Q15\n \n              \nCHRE, November 2012. An approach to assuring continuing fitness to practise based on right-touch regulation principles. Available at: http://www.professionalstandards.org.uk/library/document-detail?id=69393f02-d5a3-4ae0-a1bb-a7b437dc3485. We stressed that mechanisms for assuring the on-going fitness to practise of registrants should be based on an evaluation and quantification of the risks presented by the regulated professions. We urged regulators to develop ‘a clear understanding of what professionals do, and of the context in which they do it’ in order to understand and quantify the risks, and target their regulatory response.\n \n              \nThe Council paper states that ‘it is anticipated that if a nurse or midwife is not able to revalidate, they will lapse from the register’.\n \n              \nAs above: ‘it is anticipated that if a nurse or midwife is not able to revalidate, they will lapse from the register’.\n"